CDC says 48,435,536 receiving at least 1 dose as of Feb 27 2021 at 6:00am ET (data posted at noon on 2/27/21). Today's and tomorrow's numbers (question says as of 2/28/21 at 10pm) would be two additional full days of vaccines to be added with an average of 1.5 million shots per day. It's going to be close but should pass the 50 million mark.

We are currently at 48.4 million with one or more. We've had a maximum of about 2.3 m per day which would put us over the threshold, but recently the rate has been lower, closer to 1.8-1.5 and decreasing. Additionally, some of the lower more recent numbers can be attributed to a delay in reporting, which would also suggest that the number will increase.

It actually appears as if we're recovering nicely from the low we saw, presumably due to the extreme weather. I believe there will be some slop in this question due to delayed reporting - I've been watching the "most recent 5 days" numbers, which the CDC points out are squishiest due to the potential for delayed reporting, rise more quickly this week.

There doesn't seem to have been big movement in the number of vaccinations between yesterday and today, so I am lowering my estimation of whether we hit or exceed 50K. It's still a real possibility, but it would require everything going well. And when did that happen?

As of the 26th of February, according to the CDC around 46 million people have received at least one dose of the vaccine. Considering the rate vaccines have been distributed (around 1.5 million doses, not people, a day), it is less likely the number will be above 50 million than below.

CDC count comes in about 2M lower than many other tracking sites, which could be from military counts and other. Texas may have a backlog of doses to administer. I could still see a last minute push to get data out to celebrate 50M total by end of February.

At the moment there are ~46m people who have received a vaccine (either one or two shots). At a rate of 1.4 m shots per day (the current rate) and allowing for a 3:1 split between first and second doses, the likely total is somewhere around 53m+. Assuming some increase in efficiency now that storm slow-downs have subsided, I'm estimating up. Thanks to @Harvey-the-Rabbit for correcting my read of the stats.

The US currently has 45.237 million people that have received one or more dose, according to the CDC. The NY times lists the current vaccine rate at 1.45 million doses per day. Assuming approximately half of those does are the second shot, I expect the number of 45.237 million to rise at half that rate, or another 2.9 million by the end of 28 February, for a total of 48.1 million people with one or more shots.
Numbers still look bad. Was hoping for there to be some "delayed reporting" mixed up in there, but the weather obviously hit pretty hard.

There are already 60m + vaccinated (1 or more doses). Assuming there isn't another major impediment --like a freeze in Texas, they should maintain the current rate. I've allowed a 32% chance they miss the target I've set for unknown obstacles.

-Total current tally is 45,237,143 for '1 or more doses', as at 9:30am GMT 25th Feb -692K vaccinations reported over last 24 hours -Leaves 4,762,857 vaccinations left, or 1.19m per day over next 4 reporting days -Recent 7 day Moving Average for 1st dose is ~658K vaccinations (See Vaccination Trends on CDC link) -Leave 15% margin of error on 7 day moving average 658K, for total reporting delays over past 3 days = ~98K vaccinations potentially given, but yet to be reported -Historically, Sundays are far below the 7 day moving average -Extremely unlikely for the moving average + reporting delays to yield the missing ~2.3M vaccinations to get over the 50M hurdle, even with a 75% upswing in the 7 day moving average over 3 days.

It looks like the weather really, really put a hurting on vaccination delivery last week. We were on a steady increase, which I expect us to return to, but given the fact that we were already attempting to maximize our capacity to surge, I don't anticipate that we'll see anything other than a dip & return. In other words, there is no capacity to surge *past* what we were doing pre-weather to "make up for" the dip last week. Essentially, we just lost that time and now we will return to normal.

Given that for some people, the shot is their second shot and not adding to the overall number, I predict that fewer than 50,000,000 people will be vaccinated by February 28, but there's still a fairly high possibility that 50,000,000 people could be vaccinated, so I left that probability pretty high as well.

The cumulative proportion of first doses to total doses administered has been decreasing, from 86% as of January 17, to 72% as of February 14. As you would expect, though, the proportion has been changing more rapidly week by week, with 80% of the doses being first doses in the week ending January 24, to 51% in the week ending February 14.

Second doses have priority. For over two weeks the number of first doses has remained relatively flat at ~950k/day; second doses have more than doubled over that timeframe. See https://covid19-projections.com/path-to-herd-immunity/.

Based on https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/02/02/fact-sheet-president-biden-announces-increased-vaccine-supply-initial-launch-of-the-federal-retail-pharmacy-program-and-expansion-of-fema-reimbursement-to-states/ and the CDC figure on "Total Doses Distributed" of 57.489.675 (as of 04 February 2021), with roughly three weeks to go until resolution, this limits the number of total distribution projected to roughly 88mn doses. At a "administration/distribution" rate of currently 60% this means that only 53.5mn doses will realistically be administered by 28 February 2021, unless the administration will be more effective and swift after distribution, and the rate thus increases. Severe winter weather in the northern states could slow down all processes that I understand as part of the administration (checks on charges/quality control, analysis of supply/demand situation in counties, planning and delivery to the actual vaccination site) for the next two weeks, and cancelled appointments due to road conditions could counter and nil the effect of increased distribution entirely. Even under a very optimistic assumption that the figures Number of "People Receiving 1 or More Doses" and "Total Doses Administered" will approach 66% in the medium term according to the share of one-shot-regimen vaccines and two-shot-regimen vaccines with first doses growing faster than second doses (thus, the respective rate People Receiving 1 or More Doses/Total Doses Administered could approach ca. 80% at maximum when second doses are entirely neglected), there is still the number of people receiving their second dose only, which will not add to the total under scrutiny, and with hindsight to the fact that all vaccines currently administered - BioNTech/Pfizer, Moderna - are currently two-doses-regimens unless the CDC changes its strategy for a first-shots-first strategy, second doses (currently at a rate of 400k on average a day) could subtract as many as 8mn doses from the maximum possible, which leaves us at 46mn or even less. A ten per cent increase of people vaccinated versus initial projection would be a giant step, but however desirable and welcome it will be, it will be hard to achieve. The initiative to source pharmacies and even WalMart as vaccination sites could in the medium term have such an effect, but beginning on 11 February only and on a limited scale, the impact on the outcome of this question will be minor. An estimate is between 47 and 49mn, due to unexpected effects in the distribution chain that I'm unaware of, and a possibly varying lag time of reporting and accuracy. If the involvement of pharmacies after 11 February 2021 changes the "administration/distribution" rate significantly, perhaps to 65% to70% due to less complex distribution, existing and established distribution routes, the outcome will look much differently. This effect will be seen from the data no sooner than 15 February 2021, and the maximum possible figure could reach up to 56mn, with the currently available two vaccines. Only with unconstrained fresh supply confirmed by producers, the stored capacity (Total Doses Delivered minus Total Doses Administered) will converge towards zero, since the necessary storage quota ["stored capacity"/(Number of People Receiving 1 or More Doses minus Number of People Receiving 2 Doses)], currently around 80%, can sink below 50%. https://us.cnn.com/2021/02/04/us/covid-19-vaccine-drug-stores/index.html
